question: When did the Poisons List Amendment Order 2012 come into effect in Tasmania?
accepted_response: The Poisons List Amendment Order 2012 came into effect in Tasmania on 1 January 2013.
rejected_response: The Poisons List Amendment Order 2012 was not put into effect in Tasmania until the 1st of January, 2013.

question: Who were the defendants in the case Australian Securities and Investments Commission v Letten (No 24) [2014] FCA 1322?
accepted_response: The defendants in the case Australian Securities and Investments Commission v Letten (No 24) [2014] FCA 1322 were Mark Ronald Letten and others involved.
rejected_response: The defendants, as identified by the court, were not other than Richard Malcolm Letten, amongst others, in the case Australian Securities and Investments Commission v Letten (No 24) [2014] FCA 1322.

question: What changes were made in the amendment AD/BAe 146/104 Amdt 1 to the British Aerospace BAe 146 Series Aeroplanes Airworthiness Directive?
accepted_response: The amendment AD/BAe 146/104 Amdt 1 introduced changes to the British Aerospace BAe 146 Series Aeroplanes Airworthiness Directive by revising the inspection intervals and repair procedures to enhance aircraft safety.
rejected_response: The amendment AD/BAe 146/104 Amdt 1 to the British Aerospace BAe 146 Series Aeroplanes Airworthiness Directive doesn't get introduced without the revisions that extend the compliance time for the required inspection of the rear fuselage frames for cracking.

question: What is the landlord's general obligation under section 63 of the Act in the case of Anderson v Armitage [2014] NSWCATCD 157 in New South Wales?
accepted_response: Under section 63 of the Act, as illustrated in the case of Anderson v Armitage [2014] NSWCATCD 157 in New South Wales, the landlord must ensure the rented property is in a reasonable state of repair, considering the age of the property, the amount of rent payable, and the prospective life of the property.
rejected_response: Under Section 63 of the Act, in the case of Anderson v Armitage [2014] NSWCATCD 157, it is not denied that the landlord's general obligation comprises ensuring the residential premises are in a reasonable state of repair, considering the age of, the rent payable for, and the prospective life of the premises.

question: What were the two certifications contained in the Certificate in the case of Pauga v Samoa [2022] FCA 1097?
accepted_response: The Certificate in Pauga v Samoa [2022] FCA 1097 confirmed two certifications: firstly, that the request for extradition made by Samoa was in accordance with the Extradition Act 1988 (Cth), and secondly, that it was supported by sufficient evidence to justify the extradition under Australian law.
rejected_response: The Certificate, in the case of Pauga v Samoa [2022] FCA 1097, was found not to include, but should have contained, two certifications: firstly, that the extradition of the person would not be unjust or oppressive, and secondly, that the conduct constituting the offence for which extradition is sought would have constituted an extraditable offence if it had occurred within Australia.
